The May 1998 issue of the American Economic Review (the most prestigious
economics journal) has on pp. 398-402 a short article by J. Hay and A. Shleifer 
on "Private Enforcement of Public Laws: A Theory of Legal Reform."  

They basically argue that public law enforcement is terrible in Russia now, and 
that Russia should try to rely mostly on private law enforcement in the near future.
The reason is that private parties have much better incentives than public officials
to enforce well.  

Of course they also claim without explanation that "public enforcement is surely the 
ultimate goal of any legal reform."  And even though they also admit that public 
officials have done a terrible job at defining law, they think private enforcement 
should be of publicly defined laws, because such laws "have a degree of legitimacy
that private rules do not,"  and because they for some reason think privatley created 
rules are not publicly visible to serve as coordination points. 

