>of an article in v19, n4 of The Mathematical Intelligencer by Kirchherr
>et al.
>
>The universal prior sets the probability of an object at one over two to
>the power of its complexity (entropy).

Universal priors are useless in finite state spaces, where every prior with
full support is universal.  And unless you think infinities are essential 
to an issue like the doomsday argument, I think you're off staying with 
the simplicity of finite examples.  

